Module 1: VSCode#

In this module, we will be taking a look at one of the most popular text editors currently being used, which is Microsoft VSCode.

Microsoft VSCode#

Visual Studio Code (VSCode) is a powerful, open-source code editor developed by Microsoft. It supports a wide range of programming languages, and comes with built-in features such as debugging, version control, and code completion.

VSCode is highly customizable, allowing developers to enhance its functionality with extensions and themes. Its lightweight nature and robust feature set make it a popular choice among developers for various coding tasks.

In future modules, we will utilize VSCode to demonstrate examples of version control, through GitHub Desktop.

Installing VSCode#

To download VSCode, type “VSCode download” into the search bar, or click on the following link: https://code.visualstudio.com/download

From there, depending on the device that you have, downlaod the appropriate version.

Run the executable, and now VSCode should be successfully installed on your device.

VSCode Interface#

Once you open VSCode, you’ll be greeted with the following homepage.

The icons in the vertical left toolbar ofVSCode represent different features and sections of the editor. Let’s go through each of the icons one at a time.

  1. Explorer: This icon opens the Explorer view, where you can browse, open, and manage your files and folders within your workspace.

  2. Search: This icon brings up the search functionality, allowing you to search for text within your files and across the entire project.

  3. Source Control: This icon accesses the Source Control view, integrating with version control systems like Git to manage your source code repositories.

  4. Run and Debug: This icon opens the Run and Debug view, where you can start and control debugging sessions, configure debugging settings, and view debugging output.

  5. Extensions: This icon takes you to the Extensions view, where you can search for, install, and manage extensions that add functionality to VSCode.

The three icons directly beneath extensions are ones that I added myself, and therefore don’t need to be discussed for the purposes of this module.

Opening a Folder, Setting Up Workspace#

Opening a folder and setting up a workspace in VSCode are fundamental steps to start working on your project efficiently.

  1. Open Folder: You can open a folder by:

    • Clicking on File in the top menu and selecting Open Folder....

    • Using the keyboard shortcut Ctrl+K, Ctrl+O (or Cmd+K, Cmd+O on macOS).

    • Clicking on the Explorer icon (the first icon) in the sidebar and then clicking the Open Folder button.

  2. Navigate and Select Folder: In the dialog that appears, navigate to the folder you want to work with, select it, and click Open.

Once a folder is opened, VSCode will display the folder’s structure in the Explorer view, allowing you to browse and manage files and subfolders easily.

Creating New Files#

Once we have selected the folder in which we want to use, we need to begin populating it with the files we want to execute.

To add a new file, select the File button in the top left corner, and then New File.

Alternatively, you can also use the shortcut Ctrl+Alt+Windows+N.

From here, VSCode will ask you the type of file you wish to create.

Some options on my screen may not be present for you, as I have installed additional programs to allow for specific file types.

Let’s say I wanted to create a new Python file, called test.py.

After creating it, the file should show up in my explorer pane, as seen below.

Let’s create another file called test, but this one will be of extension .js, indicating that it’s a Javascript file.

Now, even though I have two files of the same name, they ultimately do not conflict because of the fact that their file type extensions are different.

Rearranging Editor Windows in VSCode#

Sometimes, it may be easier if we can work in split-screen mode. Doing so will lead to an easier time reading, comparing, and typing out code.

To adjust the layout of windows in VSCode, we simply click on the file we wish to move (in this example, test.js), and drag it over to the side in which we want a split-screen view.

If done correctly, our VSCode layout should look like this (the screenshot shows the explorer option collapsed).

We are not just restricted to side-by-side layouts. VSCode also allows you to stack windows on top of each other:

Executing Code#

To execute code, it is important to ensure everything is saved accordingly. If you see a small white circle beside the file name, this indicates that the file is not saved.

Let’s say I wanted to print out “Hello” in the Python terminal. I would type the code snippet print("Hello"), and currently my file is not saved, as indicated by the white circle.

Press Ctrl+S to save the file, the white circle should go away once you’ve successfully saved the notebook.

However, you may notice that there is no native support for running Python code (there is no run button). To be able to run Python (and a variety of other languages), we need to install a third party extension.

If we go to the Extensions tab in the left toolbar and search for Code Runner, we can see an extension with 28 million downloads.

This code runner extension is great for a variety of languages, such as C, Java, JavaScript, Python, and many more.

To actually run our Python code, let’s navigate to the top right corner, and click the play button (circled red).

After running the file, the output terminal should pop up.

We can see that the test.py Python file was executed, and “Hello” has been printed.

Through the third party Code Runner extension, we have successfully ran our Python file.

Let’s try executing code through a different language.

The JavaScript equivalent of print() would be console.log().

In our test.js file, let’s try outputting “Hello”.

If we were to click the run button again, similar to what was done for Python, we can see output coming out of the terminal.

Zooming into Code#

Say for example I wanted to zoom into my code, I can do so by holding down the Ctrl key and scrolling with the mouse wheel.

If this is not working, it may be because the functionality has not been enabled.

To do so, navigate to the File tab in the top left, click on Preferences, then go to Settings.

A new Settings tab should pop up, next to your test.py and test.js files.

From there, simply type “zoom” into the search bar, and ensure that the Mouse Wheel Zoom option is enabled.

Now, we are able to zoom into our code using the mouse wheel!

Changing Color Theme#

People change color themes in VSCode to customize their coding environment to suit personal preferences or improve readability. Different themes offer varying contrasts, syntax highlighting, and overall aesthetic appeal, which can enhance productivity and reduce eye strain.

Some developers prefer dark themes for their perceived reduced eye fatigue in low-light conditions, while others opt for light themes for clarity and ease of reading.

If we wanted to change the theme, we would do so by navigating to the File tab in the top left corner, clicking Preferences, Theme, then Color Theme.

From there, the two main categories in VSCode are light and dark.

If you wanted to install additional themes, simply click on + Browse Additional Color Themes.
